The `binary_prod_map_fibrant` theorem asserts that the product map of two isofibrations is an isofibration. We prove this by decomposing the product map `prod.map f.1 g.1` into the composition of `prod.map f.1 (𝟙 X')` and `prod.map (𝟙 Y) g.1`. Each of these components is a pullback of an isofibration (base change): `prod.map f.1 (𝟙 X')` is the pullback of `f` along the projection, and `prod.map (𝟙 Y) g.1` is the pullback of `g` along the projection. We use `compIsofibration` and `pullback_isIsofibration` along with standard `CategoryTheory.Limits` lemmas witnessing the pullback structure.

```lean
theorem binary_prod_map_fibrant {X Y X' Y' : K} {f : X ↠ Y} {g : X' ↠ Y'} :
    IsIsofibration (prod.map f.1 g.1) := by
  rw [← prod.map_id_comp_id_map]
  exact (compIsofibration
    ⟨_, pullback_isIsofibration f _ _ _ (isPullback_prod_map_fst f.1 _)⟩
    ⟨_, pullback_isIsofibration g _ _ _ (isPullback_prod_map_snd _ g.1).flip⟩).2
```
